{"title_page": "Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum", "text_new": "{{short description|French political activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 26 January 1929\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|03|16|1929|01|26}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Political activist <br/> Journalist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum''' (26 January 1929 \u2013 16 March 2020) was a French political activist and journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/disparition-francois-hilsum-au-croisement-de-deux-passions-686342|title=Disparition. Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum, au croisement de deux passions|date=16 March 2020|work=L'Humanit\u00e9|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHilsum came from a family of communist activists. His father, Ren\u00e9 Hilsum, was a bookseller, and his mother, Marcelle Grandjux, was a painter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article87662|title=HILSUM Ren\u00e9, Louis, Gustave, dit parfois Georges|date=22 April 2010|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article87511|title=HILSUM Marcelle [n\u00e9e GRANDJUX Agathe, Marie, Marcelle]|date=15 April 2010|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref> His brother, G\u00e9rard, was part of Undersecretary of State for Coal Auguste Lec\u0153ur's cabinet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article87564|title=HILSUM G\u00e9rard|date=15 August 2010|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref> His grandmother was a revolutionary activist and his great-uncle served as Vice-President of the [[Second International]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Buffin|first=Dider|last2=Gerbaud|first2=Dominique|date=1981|title=Les communistes: Les secrets, les rites, les m\u00e9canismes et les 120 dirigeants du plus puissant parti de France|trans-title= |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=BMVYDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT214&dq=francois+hilsum&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjng-fbwLXoAhWizIUKHd3VBDcQ6AEIOTAC#v=onepage&q=fran%C3%A7ois%20hilsum&f=false|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=FeniXX|isbn=978-2-402-16863-2}}</ref>\n\nHilsum joined the [[French Resistance]] in 1943, and became a part of the [[French Communist Party]] in April 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article50914|title=HILSUM Fran\u00e7ois|date=17 March 2020|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref>\n\nHilsum became a member of the national office of the Union of French Republican Youth in 1953. He joined the Union of Communist Youth in 1956. He became national secretary of the [[Mouvement Jeunes Communistes de France]] in 1967.\n\nFirst a boilermaker, Hilsum was also a painter and film director. He was in charge of photography for the newspaper ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'', of which he was deputy director from 1980 to 1989. He also served as editor-in-chief of ''L'Humanit\u00e9 Dimanche''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/le-chant-des-couleurs-de-francois-hilsum-638948|title=Le chant des couleurs de Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum|date=18 July 2017|work=L'Humanit\u00e9|language=French}}</ref>\n\nHe served as General Councillor of the [[canton of Sartrouville]] from 1973 to 1985, and Vice-President of the General Council of Yvelines from 1975 to 1981.\n\nStarting in 1992, Hilsum revived his youthful passion of journalism. From 13 to 24 July 2017, he exhibited his works at the Orangerie du S\u00e9nat in the [[Jardin du Luxembourg]]. He titled his display ''Arpenteur d'Imaginaires''.\n\nFran\u00e7ois Hilsum died on 16 March 2020 at the age of 91.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hilsum, Francois}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French activists]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:French Communist Party members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French political activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 26 January 1929\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|03|16|1929|01|26}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Political activist <br/> Journalist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum''' (26 January 1929 \u2013 16 March 2020) was a French political activist and journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/disparition-francois-hilsum-au-croisement-de-deux-passions-686342|title=Disparition. Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum, au croisement de deux passions|date=16 March 2020|work=L'Humanit\u00e9|language=French}}</ref>\n==Biography==\nHilsum came from a family of communist activists. His father, Ren\u00e9 Hilsum, was a bookseller, and his mother, Marcelle Grandjux, was a painter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article87662|title=HILSUM Ren\u00e9, Louis, Gustave, dit parfois Georges|date=22 April 2010|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article87511|title=HILSUM Marcelle [n\u00e9e GRANDJUX Agathe, Marie, Marcelle]|date=15 April 2010|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref> His brother, G\u00e9rard, was part of Undersecretary of State for Coal Auguste Lec\u0153ur's cabinet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article87564|title=HILSUM G\u00e9rard|date=15 August 2010|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref> His grandmother was a revolutionary activist and his great-uncle served as Vice-President of the [[Second International]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Buffin|first=Dider|last2=Gerbaud|first2=Dominique|date=1981|title=Les communistes: Les secrets, les rites, les m\u00e9canismes et les 120 dirigeants du plus puissant parti de France|trans-title= |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=BMVYDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT214&dq=francois+hilsum&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjng-fbwLXoAhWizIUKHd3VBDcQ6AEIOTAC#v=onepage&q=fran%C3%A7ois%20hilsum&f=false|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=FeniXX|isbn=978-2-402-16863-2}}</ref>\n\nHilsum joined the [[French Resistance]] in 1943, and became a part of the [[French Communist Party]] in April 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maitron.fr/spip.php?article50914|title=HILSUM Fran\u00e7ois|date=17 March 2020|work=Le Maitron|language=French}}</ref>\n\nHilsum became a member of the national office of the Union of French Republican Youth in 1953. He joined the Union of Communist Youth in 1956. He became national secretary of the [[Mouvement Jeunes Communistes de France]] in 1967.\n\nFirst a boilermaker, Hilsum was also a painter and film director. He was in charge of photography for the newspaper ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'', of which he was deputy director from 1980 to 1989. He also served as editor-in-chief of ''L'Humanit\u00e9 Dimanche''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/le-chant-des-couleurs-de-francois-hilsum-638948|title=Le chant des couleurs de Fran\u00e7ois Hilsum|date=18 July 2017|work=L'Humanit\u00e9|language=French}}</ref>\n\nHe served as General Councillor of the [[canton of Sartrouville]] from 1973 to 1985, and Vice-President of the General Council of Yvelines from 1975 to 1981.\n\nStarting in 1992, Hilsum revived his youthful passion of journalism. From 13 to 24 July 2017, he exhibited his works at the Orangerie du S\u00e9nat in the [[Jardin du Luxembourg]]. He titled his display ''Arpenteur d'Imaginaires''.\n\nFran\u00e7ois Hilsum died on 16 March 2020 at the age of 91.\n==References==\n\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French activists]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:French Communist Party members]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_Hilsum"}
{"title_page": "Bidet", "text_new": "{{short description|plumbing fixture or type of sink intended for washing the genitalia and anus of the human body}}\n[[File:Bidet Ego Kolo.jpg|thumb|A modern bidet]]\n[[File:Bidet weiss.jpg|thumb|A modern bidet of the traditional type]]\n\nA '''bidet''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-us-bidet.ogg|us|b|\u1d7b|\u02c8|d|e\u026a}} or {{IPAc-en|uk|\u02c8|b|i\u02d0|d|e\u026a}}) is a bowl or receptacle designed to be sat on for the purpose of [[washing]] the human [[Sex organ|genitalia]], [[perineum]], inner [[buttocks]], and [[human anus|anus]]. The modern variety includes a plumbed-in water supply and a drainage opening, and is thus a type of [[plumbing fixture]] subject to local hygiene regulations. The bidet is designed to promote personal hygiene, and is used after defecation, and before and after sexual intercourse. In several European countries, a bidet is today required by law to be present in every bathroom containing a [[toilet|toilet bowl]]. It was originally located in the bedroom, near the chamber-pot and the marital bed, but in modern times is located near the toilet bowl in the bathroom. Fixtures that combine a [[toilet seat]] with a washing facility include the [[electronic bidet]]. \n\nOpinions as to the necessity of the bidet vary widely over different nationalities and cultures, with anglophone nations traditionally shunning it and finding its mere existence a notorious and proverbial source of personal embarrassment and bewilderment. To those world cultures which use it habitually, such as the Islamic world, Sub-Saharan Africa, Southern Europe and the French, it is an essential and indispensable tool in maintaining good personal hygiene. \"Bidet\" is a [[French language|French]] [[loanword]] meaning \"little horse\" due to the [[List of human positions#Riding positions|straddling position]] adopted in its usage.\n\n==Applications==\nBidets are primarily used to wash and clean the genitalia, perineum, inner buttocks, and anus. Some bidets have a vertical jet intended to give easy access for washing and rinsing the perineum and anal area. The traditional separate bidet is like a wash-basin which is filled with clean water, and may then used for many other purposes such as washing feet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2017/may/01/why-wont-prudish-brits-recognise-the-bidets-brilliance |title=Why won't prudish Brits recognise the bidet's brilliance? |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 May 2017 |author=Michelle Hanson |accessdate= 13 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-28237337 |title=The imaginative ways readers use bidets|website=BBC |date=15 July 2014  |author= |accessdate= 13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n\n=== Bidet shower ===\n{{main|Bidet shower}}\n[[File:Bidee shower.jpg|upright|thumb|A Finnish bidet shower]]\nA [[bidet shower]] (also known as \"bidet spray\", \"bidet sprayer\", or \"health faucet\") is a hand-held triggered nozzle, similar to that on a kitchen sink sprayer, that delivers a spray of water to assist in [[anal cleansing]] and cleaning the genitals after defecation and urination. In contrast to a bidet that is integrated with the toilet, a bidet shower has to be held by the hands, and cleaning does not take place automatically. Bidet showers are common in countries where water is considered essential for anal cleansing.\n\nDrawbacks include the possibility of wetting a user's clothing if used carelessly. In addition, a user must be reasonably mobile and flexible to use a hand-held bidet shower.\n\n=== Conventional or standalone bidet===\n[[File:Bidet side.jpg|thumb|upright|A 20th century standalone bidet (foreground)]]\nA bidet is a plumbing fixture that is installed as a separate unit in the bathroom besides toilet, shower and sink, which users have to straddle. Some bidets resemble a large hand basin, with taps and a stopper so they can be filled up; other designs have a [[nozzle]] that squirts a jet of water to aid in cleansing.\n\n===  Add-on bidets  ===\n[[File:SB-BidetIntegrated.jpg|thumb|237px|An add-on bidet.]]\nThere are bidets that are attachable to toilet bowls, saving space and without the need to plumb in an additional unit. A bidet may be a movable or fixed nozzle attached to an existing toilet on back or side toilet rim, or replacing the toilet seat. In these cases, their use is restricted to cleaning the anus and genitals. Some bidets of this type produce a vertical water jet and others a more-or-less oblique one. Other bidets have one nozzle on the side rim aimed at both anal and genital areas, and other designs have two nozzles on the back rim. The shorter one, called the \"family nozzle\", is used for washing the area around the anus, and the longer one (\"bidet nozzle\") is designed for washing the vulva.\n\nSuch attachable bidets (also called \"combined toilets\", \"bidet attachments\", or \"add-on bidets\") are controlled either mechanically, by turning a valve, or electronically. Electronic bidets are controlled with waterproof electrical switches rather than a manual valve. There are models that have a [[Electrical element|heating element]] which blows warm air to dry the user after washing, that offer heated seats, wireless [[remote control]]s, illumination through built in [[night light]]s, or built in [[deodorizer]]s and [[activated carbon]] filters to remove odors. Further refinements include adjustable water pressure, temperature compensation, and directional spray control. Where bathroom appearance is of concern, under-the-seat mounting types have become more popular.\n\nAn add-on bidet typically connects to the existing water supply of a toilet via the addition of a [[Piping and plumbing fitting#Tee|threaded tee pipe adapter]], and requires no [[soldering]] or other [[plumbing]] work.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /> Electronic add-on bidets also require a [[GFCI]] protected grounded electrical outlet.\n\n==Usage and health ==\nPersonal hygiene is improved and maintained more accurately and easily with the use of both toilet paper and a bidet as compared to the use of toilet paper alone.<ref>{{cite news |last= Rickett |first= Oscar |date= 11 February 2018 |title= The bottom line: why it's time the bidet made a comeback |url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2018/feb/11/the-bottom-line-why-its-time-the-bidet-made-a-comeback |work= The Guardian |access-date= 29 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cohen-Mansfield |first1=J. |last2=Biddison |first2=J. R. |title=The Potential of Wash-and-Dry Toilets to Improve the Toileting Experience for Nursing Home Residents |journal=The Gerontologist |date=1 October 2005 |volume=45 |issue=5 |pages=694\u20139 |pmid=16199405 |doi=10.1093/geront/45.5.694 }}</ref> Addressing hemorrhoids and genital health issues might also be facilitated by the use of bidet fixtures.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hsu |first1=Kuo-Feng |last2=Chia |first2=Jen-Shu |last3=Jao |first3=Shu-Wen |last4=Wu |first4=Chang-Chieh |last5=Yang |first5=Hsiang-Yu |last6=Mai |first6=Chen-Ming |last7=Fu |first7=Chun-Yu |last8=Hsiao |first8=Cheng-Wen |title=Comparison of Clinical Effects Between Warm Water Spray and Sitz Bath in Post-hemorrhoidectomy Period |journal=Journal of Gastrointestinal Surgery |date=1 April 2009 |volume=13 |issue=7 |pages=1274\u20131278 |doi=10.1007/s11605-009-0876-9 |pmid=19337777 }}</ref>\n\nBecause of the large surface of the basin, after-use and routine disinfection of stand-alone bidets requires thoroughness, or microbial contamination from one user to the next could take place. Bidet attachments are sometimes included on [[hospital]] toilets because of their utility in maintaining hygiene.  Warm-water bidets may harbor dangerous microbes if not properly disinfected.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Katano |first1=Hideki |last2=Yokoyama |first2=Kumi |last3=Takei |first3=Yasushi |last4=Tazume |first4=Seiki |last5=Tsukiji |first5=Mami |last6=Matsuki |first6=Hideaki |title=A Survey on Bacterial Contamination of Lavage Water in Electric Warm-Water Lavage Toilet Seats and of the Gluteal Cleft after Lavage |journal=Journal of UOEH |date=2014 |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=135\u2013139 |doi=10.7888/juoeh.36.135 |pmid=24930878}}</ref><ref>J UOEH. 2014 Jun 1;36(2):135-9. A survey on bacterial contamination of lavage water in electric warm-water lavage toilet seats and of the gluteal cleft after lavage.Katano H1, Yokoyama K</ref>\n\n== Environmental aspects ==\nFrom an environmental standpoint, bidets can reduce the need for toilet paper.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /><ref name=\"SciAm\" /> Considering that an average person uses only {{cvt|1/8|gal|l|1}} of water for cleansing by using a bidet, much less water is used than for manufacturing toilet paper. An article in ''[[Scientific American]]'' concluded that using a bidet is \"much less stressful on the environment than using paper\".<ref name=\"SciAm\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/earth-talks-bidets/|title=Wipe or Wash? Do Bidets Save Forest and Water Resources?|last=|first=|date=|website=Scientific American|access-date=3 September 2016}}</ref> ''Scientific American'' has also reported that if the US switched to using bidets, 15 million trees could be saved every year.<ref>{{cite news |last= Albany |first= Peter |title= Wipe or Wash? Do Bidets Save Forest and Water Resources? |url= https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/earth-talks-bidets/?redirect=1 |work= Scientific American |access-date= 29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nIn [[Islam]] there are many [[Islamic toilet etiquette|strict rules concerning excretion]]; in particular anal washing with water is a strong recommendation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toilet-guru.com/islamic.php |title=Islamic Rules for Toilet Etiquette |website=Toilet Guru |date=Nov 2018 |author=Bob Cromwell |accessdate= 20 November 2018}}</ref> Consequently in Middle Eastern regions where Islam is the predominant religion, water for anal washing is provided in most toilets, usually in the form of a hand-held \"bidet shower\" or ''shattaf''.\n\n=== Prevalence ===\nBidets are becoming increasingly popular with the elderly and disabled. Combined toilet/bidet installations make self-care toileting possible for many people, affording greater independence. There are often special units with higher toilet seats allowing easier [[wheelchair|wheelchair transfer]], and with some form of electronic remote control that benefits an individual with limited mobility or otherwise requiring assistance.\n\nBidets are common bathroom fixtures in the [[Arab world]], [[West Africa]], [[Southern Europe|southern European countries]], Italy (the installation of a bidet in a bathroom has been mandatory since 1975),<ref>''Decreto ministeriale Sanit\u00e0'', 5 July 1975, art. 7.</ref> Spain (but in recent times new or renewed houses tend to have bathrooms without bidets, except the luxurious ones<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/magazine/2009/519/1251984079.html |title=\u00bfHa llegado el final del bid\u00e9? |author=Juan Carlos Rodr\u00edguez |date=6 September 2009 |language=es |website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |access-date=22 December 2016}}</ref>), and Portugal (installation is mandatory since 1975).<ref>[https://dre.pt/application/file/310347 Decreto-Lei n.\u00ba 650/75 de 18 de Novembro] (in Portuguese), 18 November 1975, art. 84</ref> They are also found in Southern Eastern Europe in countries like Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Greece. They are very popular in some South American countries, particularly Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay. Electronic bidet-integrated toilets, often with functions such as toilet seat warming, are commonly found in Japan, and are becoming more popular in other Asian countries.\n\nIn northern Europe, bidets are rare, although in Finland [[bidet shower]]s are common.<ref>[http://en.biginfinland.com/hose-always-next-every-finnish-toilet/ \"Bidets in Finland\"]</ref> Bidet showers are most commonly found in South-East Asia, South Asia, and the Middle East.\n\nIn 1980, the first \"paperless toilet\" was launched in Japan by manufacturer [[Toto Ltd.|Toto]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/life/home/2014-03-13/modern-world-even-toilets-are-becoming-paperless |title=In modern world, even toilets are becoming paperless |work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]] |access-date=2015-06-26 |date=March 13, 2014}}</ref> a combination of toilet and bidet which also dries the user after washing. These combination toilet-bidets ([[washlet]]) with seat warmers, or attachable bidets are particularly popular in Japan and South Korea, and are found in approximately 76% of Japanese households {{asof|2015|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Manjoo\"/> They are commonly found in hotels and some public facilities. These bidet-toilets, along with toilet seat and bidet units (to convert an existing toilet) are sold in many countries, including the United States.\n\nBidet seat conversions are much easier and lower cost to install than traditional bidets, and have disrupted the market for the older fixtures.<ref name=\"Manjoo\"/> The lack of acceptance of bidets can be explained by the aggressive marketing of toilet paper products, but their growing popularity can be explained by them being more environmentally friendly compared to toilet paper.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /> \n\nAfter a slow start in the 1990s, electronic bidets are starting to became more available in the United States.<ref name=\"Manjoo\"/> Popularity is steadily increasing in the US, Canada, and United Kingdom, in part because of their ability to treat [[hemorrhoids]] or [[Urinary tract infection|urogenital infections]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kiuchi|first=Teppei|last2=Asakura|first2=Keiko|last3=Nakano|first3=Makiko|last4=Omae|first4=Kazuyuki|date=2017-02-16|title=Bidet toilet use and incidence of hemorrhoids or urogenital infections: A one-year follow-up web survey|journal=Preventive Medicine Reports|volume=6|pages=121\u2013125|doi=10.1016/j.pmedr.2017.02.008|issn=2211-3355|pmc=5345955|pmid=28316906}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n''Bidet'' is a [[French language|French]] word for \"pony\", and in [[Old French]], ''bider'' meant \"to trot\". This [[etymology]] comes from the notion that one \"rides\" or [[List of human positions#Riding positions|straddles]] a bidet much like a pony is ridden. The word \"bidet\" was used in 15th century France to refer to the pet ponies that French royalty kept.<ref name=\"WTOToiletTimeline\">{{cite web|title=Toilet Timeline |url=http://www.worldtoilet.org/resources.asp?no=6 |publisher=World Toilet Organization |accessdate=20 Dec 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220192053/http://www.worldtoilet.org/resources.asp?no=6 |archivedate=December 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Boilly La Toilette intime ou la Rose effeuill\u00e9e.jpg|thumb|upright|Eighteenth century bidet in use]]\nThe bidet appears to have been an invention of French<ref>https://www.brondell.com/healthy-living-blog/who-invented-the-bidet/</ref> furniture makers in the late 17th century, although no exact date or [[inventor]] is known.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jongen |first1=Johannes |last2=Peleikis |first2=Hans-G\u00fcnter |title=Doppler-Guided Hemorrhoidal Artery Ligation: An Alternative to Hemorrhoidectomy |journal=Diseases of the Colon & Rectum |date=July 2006 |volume=49 |issue=7 |pages=1082\u20131083 |doi=10.1007/s10350-006-0553-y |pmid=16676142 }}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091220192053/http://www.worldtoilet.org/resources.asp?no=6 \"Toilet Timeline\"] on the World Toilet Organization website</ref> The earliest written reference to the bidet is in 1726 in Italy.<ref>{{cite book|date=2003|title=Storia del bidet, Un grande contenitore ideologico|trans-title=History of the bidet|url=http://www.castelvecchieditore.com/storia-del-bidet/|language=Italian|publisher=Castelvecchi|isbn=9788882101114|access-date=2017-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021163712/http://www.castelvecchieditore.com/storia-del-bidet/|archive-date=2017-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> Even though there are records of [[Maria Carolina of Austria]], Queen of Naples and Sicily, requesting a bidet for her personal bathroom in the Royal Palace of Caserta in the second half of the 18th century, the bidet did not become widespread in Italy until after WWII.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date= 2013|title= Made in Naples. Come Napoli ha civilizzato l'Europa (e come continua a farlo)|trans-title=Made in Naples. How Naples civilised Europe (And still does it)|language=Italian |location= |publisher= Addictions-Magenes Editoriale|isbn=978-8866490395}}</ref> The bidet is possibly associated with the ''chamber pot'' and the ''bourdaloue'', the latter being a small, hand-held chamber pot.\n\nHistorical antecedents and early functions of the bidet are believed to include devices used for [[contraception]].<ref>{{cite book| last1=Bullough| first1=Verne| title=Encyclopedia of Birth Control| date=2001| publisher=ABC-CLIO}}</ref> Bidets are considered ineffective by today's standards of contraception, and their use for that function was quickly abandoned and forgotten following the advent of modern contraceptives such as [[the pill]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Museum of Contraception and Abortion|title=The bidet is for vaginal rinsing|url=http://en.muvs.org/topic/the-bidet-is-for-vaginal-rinsing/}}</ref>\n\nBy 1900, due to [[plumbing]] improvements, the bidet (and [[chamber pot]]) moved from the bedroom to the bathroom, and became more convenient to fill and drain.\n\nIn 1928, in the United States, [[John Harvey Kellogg]] applied for a patent on an \"anal douche\".<ref>{{cite patent | country = United&nbsp;States | number = US1787481 A | status = patent | title = Anal douche | pubdate = Jan 6, 1931 | gdate = | fdate = Aug 22, 1928 | pridate = Aug 22, 1928 | inventor = [[John Harvey Kellogg]] | invent1 =  | invent2 =  | assign1 =  | assign2 =  | class = }}</ref> In his application, he used the term to describe a system comparable to what today might be called a bidet nozzle, which can be attached to a toilet to perform [[anal cleansing]] with water.{{Original research inline|date=February 2015}}\n\nIn 1965, the American Bidet Company featured an adjustable spray nozzle and warm water option, seeking to make the bidet a household item.<ref name=\"Manjoo\">{{cite news|last1=Manjoo|first1=Farhad|title=Electronic Bidet Toilet Seat Is the Luxury You Won't Want to Live Without|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/30/technology/personaltech/electronic-bidet-toilet-seat-is-the-luxury-you-wont-want-to-live-without.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=April 29, 2015|accessdate=2017-05-10}}</ref> The fixture was expensive, and required floor space to install; it was eventually discontinued without a replacement model.\n\nThe early 1980s saw the introduction of the electronic bidet from Japan, with names such as Clean Sense, Galaxy, Infinity, Novita, and of non-electric attachments such as Gobidet. These devices have attachments that connect to existing toilet water supplies, and can be used in bathrooms lacking the space for a separate bidet and toilet. Many models have additional features, such as instant-heating warm water, night lights, or a heated seat.\n\nThe shortage of toilet paper due to mass isolation during the Coronavirus pandemic of 2020 saw a rise in bidets within domestic homes across the globe including Australia.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Magro |first1=Rebecca |title=The Daily Flush, Toilet Paper is out, Bidets are In |url=https://www.hunterandbligh.com.au/life-and-style/the-daily-flush-toilet-paper-is-out-bidets-are-in/ |website=Hunter and Bligh |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Bidets}}\n{{Wiktionary|bidet}}\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Toilets in Japan]]\n* [[Toilet seat]]\n* [[Washlet]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Bidet.ogg|2010-04-18{{Update inline|date=May 2019}}}}\n\n{{Toilets}}\n\n[[Category:Bathroom equipment]]\n[[Category:Plumbing]]\n[[Category:French inventions]]\n[[Category:French words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|plumbing fixture or type of sink intended for washing the genitalia and anus of the human body}}\n[[File:Bidet Ego Kolo.jpg|thumb|A modern bidet]]\n[[File:Bidet weiss.jpg|thumb|A modern bidet of the traditional type]]\n\nA '''bidet''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-us-bidet.ogg|us|b|\u1d7b|\u02c8|d|e\u026a}} or {{IPAc-en|uk|\u02c8|b|i\u02d0|d|e\u026a}}) is a bowl or receptacle designed to be sat on for the purpose of [[washing]] the human [[Sex organ|genitalia]], [[perineum]], inner [[buttocks]], and [[human anus|anus]]. The modern variety includes a plumbed-in water supply and a drainage opening, and is thus a type of [[plumbing fixture]] subject to local hygiene regulations. The bidet is designed to promote personal hygiene, and is used after defecation, and before and after sexual intercourse. In several European countries, a bidet is today required by law to be present in every bathroom containing a [[toilet|toilet bowl]]. It was originally located in the bedroom, near the chamber-pot and the marital bed, but in modern times is located near the toilet bowl in the bathroom. Fixtures that combine a [[toilet seat]] with a washing facility include the [[electronic bidet]]. \n\nOpinions as to the necessity of the bidet vary widely over different nationalities and cultures, with anglophone nations traditionally shunning it and finding its mere existence a notorious and proverbial source of personal embarrassment and bewilderment. To those world cultures which use it habitually, such as the Islamic world, Sub-Saharan Africa, Southern Europe and the French, it is an essential and indispensable tool in maintaining good personal hygiene. \"Bidet\" is a [[French language|French]] [[loanword]] meaning \"little horse\" due to the [[List of human positions#Riding positions|straddling position]] adopted in its usage.\n\n==Applications==\nBidets are primarily used to wash and clean the genitalia, perineum, inner buttocks, and anus. Some bidets have a vertical jet intended to give easy access for washing and rinsing the perineum and anal area. The traditional separate bidet is like a wash-basin which is filled with clean water, and may then used for many other purposes such as washing feet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2017/may/01/why-wont-prudish-brits-recognise-the-bidets-brilliance |title=Why won't prudish Brits recognise the bidet's brilliance? |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 May 2017 |author=Michelle Hanson |accessdate= 13 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-28237337 |title=The imaginative ways readers use bidets|website=BBC |date=15 July 2014  |author= |accessdate= 13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n\n=== Bidet shower ===\n{{main|Bidet shower}}\n[[File:Bidee shower.jpg|upright|thumb|A Finnish bidet shower]]\nA [[bidet shower]] (also known as \"bidet spray\", \"bidet sprayer\", or \"health faucet\") is a hand-held triggered nozzle, similar to that on a kitchen sink sprayer, that delivers a spray of water to assist in [[anal cleansing]] and cleaning the genitals after defecation and urination. In contrast to a bidet that is integrated with the toilet, a bidet shower has to be held by the hands, and cleaning does not take place automatically. Bidet showers are common in countries where water is considered essential for anal cleansing.\n\nDrawbacks include the possibility of wetting a user's clothing if used carelessly. In addition, a user must be reasonably mobile and flexible to use a hand-held bidet shower.\n\n=== Conventional or standalone bidet===\n[[File:Bidet side.jpg|thumb|upright|A 20th century standalone bidet (foreground)]]\nA bidet is a plumbing fixture that is installed as a separate unit in the bathroom besides toilet, shower and sink, which users have to straddle. Some bidets resemble a large hand basin, with taps and a stopper so they can be filled up; other designs have a [[nozzle]] that squirts a jet of water to aid in cleansing.\n\n===  Add-on bidets  ===\n[[File:SB-BidetIntegrated.jpg|thumb|237px|An add-on bidet.]]\nThere are bidets that are attachable to toilet bowls, saving space and without the need to plumb in an additional unit. A bidet may be a movable or fixed nozzle attached to an existing toilet on back or side toilet rim, or replacing the toilet seat. In these cases, their use is restricted to cleaning the anus and genitals. Some bidets of this type produce a vertical water jet and others a more-or-less oblique one. Other bidets have one nozzle on the side rim aimed at both anal and genital areas, and other designs have two nozzles on the back rim. The shorter one, called the \"family nozzle\", is used for washing the area around the anus, and the longer one (\"bidet nozzle\") is designed for washing the vulva.\n\nSuch attachable bidets (also called \"combined toilets\", \"bidet attachments\", or \"add-on bidets\") are controlled either mechanically, by turning a valve, or electronically. Electronic bidets are controlled with waterproof electrical switches rather than a manual valve. There are models that have a [[Electrical element|heating element]] which blows warm air to dry the user after washing, that offer heated seats, wireless [[remote control]]s, illumination through built in [[night light]]s, or built in [[deodorizer]]s and [[activated carbon]] filters to remove odors. Further refinements include adjustable water pressure, temperature compensation, and directional spray control. Where bathroom appearance is of concern, under-the-seat mounting types have become more popular.\n\nAn add-on bidet typically connects to the existing water supply of a toilet via the addition of a [[Piping and plumbing fitting#Tee|threaded tee pipe adapter]], and requires no [[soldering]] or other [[plumbing]] work.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /> Electronic add-on bidets also require a [[GFCI]] protected grounded electrical outlet.\n\n==Usage and health ==\nPersonal hygiene is improved and maintained more accurately and easily with the use of both toilet paper and a bidet as compared to the use of toilet paper alone.<ref>{{cite news |last= Rickett |first= Oscar |date= 11 February 2018 |title= The bottom line: why it's time the bidet made a comeback |url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2018/feb/11/the-bottom-line-why-its-time-the-bidet-made-a-comeback |work= The Guardian |access-date= 29 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cohen-Mansfield |first1=J. |last2=Biddison |first2=J. R. |title=The Potential of Wash-and-Dry Toilets to Improve the Toileting Experience for Nursing Home Residents |journal=The Gerontologist |date=1 October 2005 |volume=45 |issue=5 |pages=694\u20139 |pmid=16199405 |doi=10.1093/geront/45.5.694 }}</ref> Addressing hemorrhoids and genital health issues might also be facilitated by the use of bidet fixtures.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hsu |first1=Kuo-Feng |last2=Chia |first2=Jen-Shu |last3=Jao |first3=Shu-Wen |last4=Wu |first4=Chang-Chieh |last5=Yang |first5=Hsiang-Yu |last6=Mai |first6=Chen-Ming |last7=Fu |first7=Chun-Yu |last8=Hsiao |first8=Cheng-Wen |title=Comparison of Clinical Effects Between Warm Water Spray and Sitz Bath in Post-hemorrhoidectomy Period |journal=Journal of Gastrointestinal Surgery |date=1 April 2009 |volume=13 |issue=7 |pages=1274\u20131278 |doi=10.1007/s11605-009-0876-9 |pmid=19337777 }}</ref>\n\nBecause of the large surface of the basin, after-use and routine disinfection of stand-alone bidets requires thoroughness, or microbial contamination from one user to the next could take place. Bidet attachments are sometimes included on [[hospital]] toilets because of their utility in maintaining hygiene.  Warm-water bidets may harbor dangerous microbes if not properly disinfected.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Katano |first1=Hideki |last2=Yokoyama |first2=Kumi |last3=Takei |first3=Yasushi |last4=Tazume |first4=Seiki |last5=Tsukiji |first5=Mami |last6=Matsuki |first6=Hideaki |title=A Survey on Bacterial Contamination of Lavage Water in Electric Warm-Water Lavage Toilet Seats and of the Gluteal Cleft after Lavage |journal=Journal of UOEH |date=2014 |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=135\u2013139 |doi=10.7888/juoeh.36.135 |pmid=24930878}}</ref><ref>J UOEH. 2014 Jun 1;36(2):135-9. A survey on bacterial contamination of lavage water in electric warm-water lavage toilet seats and of the gluteal cleft after lavage.Katano H1, Yokoyama K</ref>\n\n== Environmental aspects ==\nFrom an environmental standpoint, bidets can reduce the need for toilet paper.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /><ref name=\"SciAm\" /> Considering that an average person uses only {{cvt|1/8|gal|l|1}} of water for cleansing by using a bidet, much less water is used than for manufacturing toilet paper. An article in ''[[Scientific American]]'' concluded that using a bidet is \"much less stressful on the environment than using paper\".<ref name=\"SciAm\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/earth-talks-bidets/|title=Wipe or Wash? Do Bidets Save Forest and Water Resources?|last=|first=|date=|website=Scientific American|access-date=3 September 2016}}</ref> ''Scientific American'' has also reported that if the US switched to using bidets, 15 million trees could be saved every year.<ref>{{cite news |last= Albany |first= Peter |title= Wipe or Wash? Do Bidets Save Forest and Water Resources? |url= https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/earth-talks-bidets/?redirect=1 |work= Scientific American |access-date= 29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nIn [[Islam]] there are many [[Islamic toilet etiquette|strict rules concerning excretion]]; in particular anal washing with water is a strong recommendation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toilet-guru.com/islamic.php |title=Islamic Rules for Toilet Etiquette |website=Toilet Guru |date=Nov 2018 |author=Bob Cromwell |accessdate= 20 November 2018}}</ref> Consequently in Middle Eastern regions where Islam is the predominant religion, water for anal washing is provided in most toilets, usually in the form of a hand-held \"bidet shower\" or ''shattaf''.\n\n=== Prevalence ===\nBidets are becoming increasingly popular with the elderly and disabled. Combined toilet/bidet installations make self-care toileting possible for many people, affording greater independence. There are often special units with higher toilet seats allowing easier [[wheelchair|wheelchair transfer]], and with some form of electronic remote control that benefits an individual with limited mobility or otherwise requiring assistance.\n\nBidets are common bathroom fixtures in the [[Arab world]], [[West Africa]], [[Southern Europe|southern European countries]], Italy (the installation of a bidet in a bathroom has been mandatory since 1975),<ref>''Decreto ministeriale Sanit\u00e0'', 5 July 1975, art. 7.</ref> Spain (but in recent times new or renewed houses tend to have bathrooms without bidets, except the luxurious ones<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/magazine/2009/519/1251984079.html |title=\u00bfHa llegado el final del bid\u00e9? |author=Juan Carlos Rodr\u00edguez |date=6 September 2009 |language=es |website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |access-date=22 December 2016}}</ref>), and Portugal (installation is mandatory since 1975).<ref>[https://dre.pt/application/file/310347 Decreto-Lei n.\u00ba 650/75 de 18 de Novembro] (in Portuguese), 18 November 1975, art. 84</ref> They are also found in Southern Eastern Europe in countries like Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Greece. They are very popular in some South American countries, particularly Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay. Electronic bidet-integrated toilets, often with functions such as toilet seat warming, are commonly found in Japan, and are becoming more popular in other Asian countries.\n\nIn northern Europe, bidets are rare, although in Finland [[bidet shower]]s are common.<ref>[http://en.biginfinland.com/hose-always-next-every-finnish-toilet/ \"Bidets in Finland\"]</ref> Bidet showers are most commonly found in South-East Asia, South Asia, and the Middle East.\n\nIn 1980, the first \"paperless toilet\" was launched in Japan by manufacturer [[Toto Ltd.|Toto]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/life/home/2014-03-13/modern-world-even-toilets-are-becoming-paperless |title=In modern world, even toilets are becoming paperless |work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]] |access-date=2015-06-26 |date=March 13, 2014}}</ref> a combination of toilet and bidet which also dries the user after washing. These combination toilet-bidets ([[washlet]]) with seat warmers, or attachable bidets are particularly popular in Japan and South Korea, and are found in approximately 76% of Japanese households {{asof|2015|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Manjoo\"/> They are commonly found in hotels and some public facilities. These bidet-toilets, along with toilet seat and bidet units (to convert an existing toilet) are sold in many countries, including the United States.\n\nBidet seat conversions are much easier and lower cost to install than traditional bidets, and have disrupted the market for the older fixtures.<ref name=\"Manjoo\"/> The lack of acceptance of bidets can be explained by the aggressive marketing of toilet paper products, but their growing popularity can be explained by them being more environmentally friendly compared to toilet paper.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /> \n\nAfter a slow start in the 1990s, electronic bidets are starting to became more available in the United States.<ref name=\"Manjoo\"/> Popularity is steadily increasing in the US, Canada, and United Kingdom, in part because of their ability to treat [[hemorrhoids]] or [[Urinary tract infection|urogenital infections]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kiuchi|first=Teppei|last2=Asakura|first2=Keiko|last3=Nakano|first3=Makiko|last4=Omae|first4=Kazuyuki|date=2017-02-16|title=Bidet toilet use and incidence of hemorrhoids or urogenital infections: A one-year follow-up web survey|journal=Preventive Medicine Reports|volume=6|pages=121\u2013125|doi=10.1016/j.pmedr.2017.02.008|issn=2211-3355|pmc=5345955|pmid=28316906}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n''Bidet'' is a [[French language|French]] word for \"pony\", and in [[Old French]], ''bider'' meant \"to trot\". This [[etymology]] comes from the notion that one \"rides\" or [[List of human positions#Riding positions|straddles]] a bidet much like a pony is ridden. The word \"bidet\" was used in 15th century France to refer to the pet ponies that French royalty kept.<ref name=\"WTOToiletTimeline\">{{cite web|title=Toilet Timeline |url=http://www.worldtoilet.org/resources.asp?no=6 |publisher=World Toilet Organization |accessdate=20 Dec 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220192053/http://www.worldtoilet.org/resources.asp?no=6 |archivedate=December 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Boilly La Toilette intime ou la Rose effeuill\u00e9e.jpg|thumb|upright|Eighteenth century bidet in use]]\nThe bidet appears to have been an invention of French<ref>https://www.brondell.com/healthy-living-blog/who-invented-the-bidet/</ref> furniture makers in the late 17th century, although no exact date or [[inventor]] is known.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jongen |first1=Johannes |last2=Peleikis |first2=Hans-G\u00fcnter |title=Doppler-Guided Hemorrhoidal Artery Ligation: An Alternative to Hemorrhoidectomy |journal=Diseases of the Colon & Rectum |date=July 2006 |volume=49 |issue=7 |pages=1082\u20131083 |doi=10.1007/s10350-006-0553-y |pmid=16676142 }}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091220192053/http://www.worldtoilet.org/resources.asp?no=6 \"Toilet Timeline\"] on the World Toilet Organization website</ref> The earliest written reference to the bidet is in 1726 in Italy.<ref>{{cite book|date=2003|title=Storia del bidet, Un grande contenitore ideologico|trans-title=History of the bidet|url=http://www.castelvecchieditore.com/storia-del-bidet/|language=Italian|publisher=Castelvecchi|isbn=9788882101114|access-date=2017-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021163712/http://www.castelvecchieditore.com/storia-del-bidet/|archive-date=2017-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> Even though there are records of [[Maria Carolina of Austria]], Queen of Naples and Sicily, requesting a bidet for her personal bathroom in the Royal Palace of Caserta in the second half of the 18th century, the bidet did not become widespread in Italy until after WWII.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date= 2013|title= Made in Naples. Come Napoli ha civilizzato l'Europa (e come continua a farlo)|trans-title=Made in Naples. How Naples civilised Europe (And still does it)|language=Italian |location= |publisher= Addictions-Magenes Editoriale|isbn=978-8866490395}}</ref> The bidet is possibly associated with the ''chamber pot'' and the ''bourdaloue'', the latter being a small, hand-held chamber pot.\n\nHistorical antecedents and early functions of the bidet are believed to include devices used for [[contraception]].<ref>{{cite book| last1=Bullough| first1=Verne| title=Encyclopedia of Birth Control| date=2001| publisher=ABC-CLIO}}</ref> Bidets are considered ineffective by today's standards of contraception, and their use for that function was quickly abandoned and forgotten following the advent of modern contraceptives such as [[the pill]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Museum of Contraception and Abortion|title=The bidet is for vaginal rinsing|url=http://en.muvs.org/topic/the-bidet-is-for-vaginal-rinsing/}}</ref>\n\nBy 1900, due to [[plumbing]] improvements, the bidet (and [[chamber pot]]) moved from the bedroom to the bathroom, and became more convenient to fill and drain.\n\nIn 1928, in the United States, [[John Harvey Kellogg]] applied for a patent on an \"anal douche\".<ref>{{cite patent | country = United&nbsp;States | number = US1787481 A | status = patent | title = Anal douche | pubdate = Jan 6, 1931 | gdate = | fdate = Aug 22, 1928 | pridate = Aug 22, 1928 | inventor = [[John Harvey Kellogg]] | invent1 =  | invent2 =  | assign1 =  | assign2 =  | class = }}</ref> In his application, he used the term to describe a system comparable to what today might be called a bidet nozzle, which can be attached to a toilet to perform [[anal cleansing]] with water.{{Original research inline|date=February 2015}}\n\nIn 1965, the American Bidet Company featured an adjustable spray nozzle and warm water option, seeking to make the bidet a household item.<ref name=\"Manjoo\">{{cite news|last1=Manjoo|first1=Farhad|title=Electronic Bidet Toilet Seat Is the Luxury You Won't Want to Live Without|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/30/technology/personaltech/electronic-bidet-toilet-seat-is-the-luxury-you-wont-want-to-live-without.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=April 29, 2015|accessdate=2017-05-10}}</ref> The fixture was expensive, and required floor space to install; it was eventually discontinued without a replacement model.\n\nThe early 1980s saw the introduction of the electronic bidet from Japan, with names such as Clean Sense, Galaxy, Infinity, Novita, and of non-electric attachments such as Gobidet. These devices have attachments that connect to existing toilet water supplies, and can be used in bathrooms lacking the space for a separate bidet and toilet. Many models have additional features, such as instant-heating warm water, night lights, or a heated seat.\n\nThe shortage of toilet paper due to mass isolation during the Coronavirus outbreak of 2020 saw a rise in bidets within domestic homes across the globe including Australia.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Magro |first1=Rebecca |title=The Daily Flush, Toilet Paper is out, Bidets are In |url=https://www.hunterandbligh.com.au/life-and-style/the-daily-flush-toilet-paper-is-out-bidets-are-in/ |website=Hunter and Bligh |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Bidets}}\n{{Wiktionary|bidet}}\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Toilets in Japan]]\n* [[Toilet seat]]\n* [[Washlet]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Bidet.ogg|2010-04-18{{Update inline|date=May 2019}}}}\n\n{{Toilets}}\n\n[[Category:Bathroom equipment]]\n[[Category:Plumbing]]\n[[Category:French inventions]]\n[[Category:French words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Thirdnewscaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bidet"}
{"title_page": "Jules Carbotte", "text_new": "{Jules P Carbotte is a prisioner, did years in the Joyceville pen because she did not self isolate during COVID-19.\n{Orphan|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Jules P. Carbotte\n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date = 1938-03-26\n| birth_place = Long Beach, CA\n| death_date = 2019-04-05<ref name=\":1\" />\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| pronounce = \n| residence = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = \n| workplaces = [[Cornell University]], <br> [[McMaster University]]\n| patrons = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Manitoba]], <br> [[McGill University]]\n| thesis_title = Positron annihilation in metals\n| thesis_url = http://digitool.Library.McGill.CA:80/R/-?func=dbin-jump-full&object_id=115375&silo_library=GEN01\n| thesis_year = <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor = S. Kahana\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = [[Condensed matter physics]]\n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[Canadian Association of Physicists|CAP]] Herzberg Medal (1974), Steacie Prize (1975)\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children = \n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Jules P. Carbotte''' (March 26,1938 \u2013 April 5, 2019) was a Canadian physicist, [[professor]] at [[McMaster University]] and a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada]]. His research interests spanned many areas of theoretical [[condensed matter physics]]. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nCarbotte was born in [[Long Beach, California]], on March 26, 1938, when his parents, Leon and Pauline Carbotte, were visiting California on an extended winter holiday from their home in [[Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He grew up in a [[Franco-Manitoban|French-speaking]] community in Manitoba and attended the [[Universit\u00e9 de Saint-Boniface]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCarbotte received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree with honors in physics in 1960 from the [[University of Manitoba]]. He received a [[Master of Science|Masters of Science]] degree in physics in 1961 and [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in physics from [[McGill University]] in 1963.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://julescarbotte.weebly.com/index.html|title=Jules P. Carbotte|website=Jules P. Carbotte|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525170213/http://www.physics.mcmaster.ca/people/faculty/Carbotte_JP_h.html|title=Jules Carbotte|date=29 Jul 2016|publisher=mcmaster.ca|accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref> His PhD research in condensed matter physics focused on refinements to theoretical models of [[positron]] [[Electron\u2013positron annihilation|annihilation]] in metals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=P.|first=Carbotte, Jules.|date=1964|title=Positron annihilation in metals.|url=http://digitool.Library.McGill.CA:80/R/-?func=dbin-jump-full&object_id=115375&silo_library=GEN01}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter finishing his PhD, spent two years as a research associate in the Physics Department of [[Cornell University]]. In 1965 he returned to Canada and became an assistant professor in the department of Physics at [[McMaster University]]. In 1967, he took a position at [[McGill University]] then returned to McMaster in 1968 where he stayed for the rest of his career.<ref name=\":1\" /> He became an associate professor in 1972 and a university professor at McMaster in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.science.ca/scientists/scientistprofile.php?pID=329&pg=3|title=science.ca : Jules P. Carbotte|website=www.science.ca|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref> \n\nIn 1988, Carbotte became the founding director of the [[superconductivity]] program of the [[Canadian Institute for Advanced Research]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cifar.ca/cifarnews/2019/04/15/in-memoriam-jules-carbotte-(1938-2019)|title=In Memoriam - Jules Carbotte|website=CIFAR|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref> He retired in 1998.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://secretariat.mcmaster.ca/app/uploads/2018/11/Distinguished_Univ_Prof.pdf|title=Distinguished University Professors|publisher=mcmaster.ca|accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOver his career, Carbotte contributed to many different areas of condensed matter theory. His work includes theoretical calculations of positron annihilation and [[electron]]-[[phonon]] interaction in metals. He has also contributed to the theoretical understanding of dilute metallic [[Alloy|alloys]], where a small amount of one metallic element is dissolved in another metallic element. He has also worked to understand the microscopic origins of [[superconductivity]], especially in [[High-temperature superconductivity|high-temperature superconducting]] oxides.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cifar.ca/bio/jules-p-carbotte|title=Bio - Jules P. Carbotte|website=CIFAR|language=en|access-date=2018-11-28}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Recognitions ==\n\n* 1974 [[Canadian Association of Physicists|CAP]] Herzberg Medal <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cap.ca/programs/medals-and-awards/medals-research/herzberg-medal/previous-winners-hm/|title=CAP Herzberg Medal - Previous Winners - Canadian Association of Physicists|work=Canadian Association of Physicists|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*1974 Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rsc-src.ca/en/search-fellows|title=FELLOWS DIRECTORY {{!}} The Royal Society of Canada|website=rsc-src.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n* 1975 Steacie Prize <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.steacieprize.ca/recipients_e.html|title=The Steacie Prize - Recipients|last=Sciences|first=Steacie Institute for Molecular|website=www.steacieprize.ca|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n* 1979 [[Canadian Association of Physicists|CAP]] Gold Medal\n* 1981 Metal Physics Medal\n*1987 Fellow of the [[Canadian Institute for Advanced Research]]\n* 1996 University Distinguished Professor, McMaster University <ref name=\":0\" />\n*1994 Honorary [[Doctor of Science|DSc]], [[University of Waterloo]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uwaterloo.ca/secretariat/committees-and-councils/honorary-degrees-committee/honorary-degrees-granted/c-d|title=C - D|date=2012-05-18|website=Secretariat|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n*1999 Honorary [[Doctor of Science|DSc]], University of Manitoba <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://umanitoba.ca/admin/governance/senate/hdr/1002.html|title=University of Manitoba - University Governance - Jules Pierre Carbotte, D.Sc., May 27, 1999|website=umanitoba.ca|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n*2000 Honorary [[Doctor of Science|DSc]], [[Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usherbrooke.ca/relations-medias/communiques/archives/2000/juin/communiques-detail/c/3285/|title=L'Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke d\u00e9cerne un doctorat d'honneur en sciences \u00e0 l'\u00e9minent physicien canadien Jules Carbotte|date=2000-06-14|website=Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke|language=fr|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n*2010 Honorary [[Doctor of Science|DSc]], McMaster University <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailynews.mcmaster.ca/articles/mcmaster-university-announces-honorary-degree-recipients/|title=McMaster University announces honorary degree recipients|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=Carbotte|first=J. P.|date=1990-10-01|title=Properties of boson-exchange superconductors|journal=Reviews of Modern Physics|volume=62|issue=4|pages=1027\u20131157|doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.62.1027|bibcode=1990RvMP...62.1027C}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Prohammer|first=M.|last2=Perez-Gonzalez|first2=A.|last3=Carbotte|first3=J. P.|date=1993-06-01|title=Thermodynamics of a retarded d-wave superconductor with resonant impurity scattering|journal=Physical Review B|volume=47|issue=22|pages=15152\u201315158|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.47.15152|pmid=10005888|bibcode=1993PhRvB..4715152P}}\n\n== Personal life ==\nCarbotte married Ramona DePauw in 1959 and remained together until his death 59 years later. The couple met during a first year summer school class in physics while they were both undergraduates at the University of Manitoba. They had two daughters Christine and Suzanne.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carbotte, Jules}}\n[[Category:McMaster University faculty]]\n[[Category:Canadian physicists]]\n\n\n{{Canada-scientist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Jules P. Carbotte\n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date = 1938-03-26\n| birth_place = Long Beach, CA\n| death_date = 2019-04-05<ref name=\":1\" />\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| pronounce = \n| residence = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = \n| workplaces = [[Cornell University]], <br> [[McMaster University]]\n| patrons = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Manitoba]], <br> [[McGill University]]\n| thesis_title = Positron annihilation in metals\n| thesis_url = http://digitool.Library.McGill.CA:80/R/-