e most recent [[Principal (school)|principal]] was Nicola Connery. The school was formed when, in 1989, the [[Single-sex school|all-boys']] [[Annadale Grammar School]] and the all-girls' [[Carolan Grammar School]] merged to become a single co-educational school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/history.php |title=20 statements about the college |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=29 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212025105/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/history.php |archive-date=12 December 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWellington College was founded in 1989 after [[Annadale Grammar School|Annadale Boys]] and [[Carolan Grammar School|Carolan Girls]] merged. The school is named after [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]]. The school moved to its current location on Carolan Road in 2002, which included 2 new rugby pitches, a gravel pitch, an astro pitch and a running track.\n\n==Principals==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n ! # !! Name !! Tenure\n|-\n| 1 \n| Mr Derick Woods\n|1989-1995\n|-\n| 2\n| Mrs Jacqueline Weir\n| 1995-2000\n|-\n| 3\n| Mr Ronnie Hassard\n| 2000-2004\n|-\n| 4\n| Mrs Heather Reid\n| 2004-2009\n|-\n| 5\n| Mr Matthew Pitts\n| 2010-2014\n|-\n| 6\n| Mrs Nicola Connery\n| 2015-2016\n|-\n| 7\n| Mr David Castles\n| 2017-present\n|}\n\n==Uniform==\nThe Wellington [[blazer]] takes its blue colour from that of the [[British Army]] during the 19th century<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kildare.ie/Monasterevin-Historical-Society/hussars.htm |title=Hussars |publisher=Kildare.ie |date=26 March 2003 |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref> which was the [[uniform]] worn by the [[Duke of Wellington]] during his service. The sports kit for Wellington was changed in May 2011.\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\nWellington offers a number of extracurricular activities to its pupils. These normally run after school or during lunch time, and are generally overseen by members of the teaching or library staff. In some cases a specialist in a particular subject may be invited to take a course (e.g. In January 2008 Neil Best and Rob Dewey helped with rugby training)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/index.php |title=Extra Curricular &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510014955/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/index.php |archive-date=10 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nActivities include;\n*Scripture Union<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/su.php |title=Scripture Union &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065420/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/su.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Science Club<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/science-club.php |title=Science Club &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065428/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/science-club.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Art Club<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/art-club.php |title=Art Club &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065434/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/art-club.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Concert Band<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/band---orchestra.php |title=Band & Orchestra &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065439/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/band---orchestra.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Boy's Choir<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/boys-choir.php |title=Boys Choir &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065443/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/boys-choir.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Junior Choir<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/junior-choir.php |title=Junior Choir &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065446/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/junior-choir.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Senior Choir<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/senior-choir.php |title=Senior Choir &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065458/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/senior-choir.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Junior Brass Group<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/junior-brass-group.php |title=Junior Brass Group &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065502/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/junior-brass-group.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Senior Brass Group<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/senior-brass-group.php |title=Senior Brass Group &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065508/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/senior-brass-group.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Woodwind Group<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/woodwind-groups.php |title=Woodwind Groups &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065513/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/woodwind-groups.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*String Trio<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/string.php |title=String Trio &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065526/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/music/extra-curricular/string.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*School Council\n\n==Awards==\n* 2005 [[International School Award]] <ref>[http://www.globalgateway.org.uk/pdf/Full%202005.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719073848/http://www.globalgateway.org.uk/pdf/Full%202005.pdf |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* The school KLQ team won the [[Kids' Lit Quiz]] in 2007 at the world final in [[Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kidslitquiz.com/world-final/2007 |title=2007 - Kids' Lit Quiz |publisher=Kidslitquiz.com |accessdate=29 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627171628/http://www.kidslitquiz.com/world-final/2007 |archive-date=27 June 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Wellington received an award for raising money and providing donations of items to [[Haiti]] after the earthquake.\n*In 2012, three pupils in Year 11 won the Northern Irish Regional heat of the WorldWise Geography quiz and then became runners up the next year. The team consisted of Jack Taylor (captain), Adam Callender and Marc Thompson.\n\n===Future Chef 2011===\nChristopher Marshall, (a then year 10 pupil) represented Wellington in the [[Northern Ireland Future Chef]] competition 2011. He won the Northern Ireland competition on Wednesday 2 February 2011. He was then entered into the Future Chef Final and travelled to London on 21 March 2011 for the competition, getting the chance to meet [[Ainsley Harriott]] and [[Brian Turner (chef)|Brian Turner]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/future-chef-2011.php |title=Future Chef 2011 &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327065629/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/future-chef-2011.php |archive-date=27 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Mathematical Olympiad 2011===\nDale Walmsley, (a then year 12 student at Wellington) was awarded a gold medal and a book prize in the [[United Kingdom Mathematics Trust|UK Intermediate Mathematical Olympiad]]. Dale was the only student from Northern Ireland to achieve a gold medal and book prize in the Olympiad. This accolade means that he is ranked within the top 50 mathematicians of his age in the UK. Mr Cantley, head of the Mathematics department at Wellington at that time, stated that everyone at the College is absolutely delighted by Dale\u2019s achievement. Mr Cantley, who taught Dale since third year, stated that Dale is a truly remarkable young mathematician, having obtained an A* in [[GCSE]] Mathematics at only 14, an A* in both GCSE Additional Mathematics and [[GCE Advanced Level|A Level]] Mathematics at 15 and first place in the 2010 Northern Ireland GCSE Additional Mathematics examination.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/index.php |title=Index &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509185337/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/index.php |archive-date=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===BT Young Scientist and Technology Exhibition===\n====2011====\n*Highly Commended Award\n*Eco Award\n\n====2012====\n*Highly Commended Award (Snail slime and muscle power-the secret of their success)\n\n====2014====\n*Highly Commended Award\n*Display Award (x2)\n*1st place in Senior Biological Category\n*Institute of Physics Award\n*Best School in Northern Ireland Award\n\n==BT Young Scientist and Technology Exhibition==\n\n===2011===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Pupil\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year (at time of event)\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Project\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n|-\n| Christopher Lynn\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 9\n| rowspan=\"3\"| WCBinit: Optimising Litter Collection in the canteen\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Highly Commended Award <br> Eco Award\n|-\n| Mitchell McKee\n|-\n| Jordan Knocker\n|}\nTeachers involved:\n*Yvonne Johnston (Head of Science)\n*David Cardwell\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/galleries/events/bt-young-scientist-competition-2010.php |title=Galleries - BT Young Scientist 2010 &#124; Wellington College |publisher=Wellingtoncollegebelfast.org |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004195725/http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/galleries/events/bt-young-scientist-competition-2010.php |archive-date=4 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btyoungscientist.com/ |title=BT Young Scientist & Technology Exhibition - RDS Dublin - Ireland January 9th - 12th 2013 |publisher=Btyoungscientist.com |date= |accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wellington College Belfast 2011.jpg|thumb|Back Row: David Cardwell <br> Middle Row: Mitchell McKee, Caitr\u00edona Ruane, Peter Morris, Yvonne Johnston <br>Front Row: Jordan Knocker, Christopher Lynn]]\nChristopher Lynn, Jordan Knocker and Mitchell McKee were in the team. The boys conducted an experiment on how to cut down litter in the school. In October 2010, they found out they had got through to the final in the RDS in Dublin. In January, the three boys went to Dublin with science teacher Stephen Wilson, as David Cardwell was unable to attend on the first day and Yvonne Johnston had work in school. David Cardwell was in Dublin for the second and third day of the competition and Yvonne Johnston attended the exhibition on the final day. The boys' exhibition was on feature in the school foyer from January 2011 to April 2011, after which it was placed safely in storage. The exhibition was re-displayed in Science Lab 102 in August 2011.\n\n===2012===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Pupil\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year (at time of event)\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Project\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n|-\n| Hali Sharpe\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 10\n| rowspan=\"3\"| All washed up\n| rowspan=\"3\"|\n|-\n| Courtney Henderson-Storey\n|-\n| Rachel Gardiner\n|-\n| Sarah Jackson\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Changes in diversity and population size of woodlice species following disturbance\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n| Chelsea Anderson\n|-\n| Amy Flanagan\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 11\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Snail slime and muscle power-the secret of their success\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Highly Commended Award\n|-\n| Amy McNamara\n|-\n| Olivia McCulla\n|-\n| Evelyn Workman\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 12\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Remembering what we forgot\n| rowspan=\"3\"|\n|-\n| Gemma Hawthorne\n|-\n| Eryn Anderson \n|}\n\nTeachers involved:\n*Yvonne Johnston (Head of Science)\n*David Cardwell\nIn May 2011, Science Club members were given a new leaflet on the upcoming 2012 BT Young Scientist & Technology Exhibition. Yvonne Johnston would like the event to go ahead and several pupils showed interest. Four out of five groups got through to the Final in January 2012. One group out of the four won an award, a Highly Commended award. On 17 January 2012, Lynn said he is likely to return after mentioning a project to Yvonne Johnston.\n\n\"Snail slime and muscle power-the secret of their success\", \"Changes in diversity and population size of woodlice species following disturbance\", \"All washed up\" and \"Remembering what we forget\" were the 4 projects that got through to the Final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.btyoungscientist.com/downloads/2012-qualified-all.pdf |publisher=Btyoungscientist.com |title=Young Scientist listing |accessdate=29 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127121103/http://www.btyoungscientist.com/downloads/2012-qualified-all.pdf |archive-date=27 January 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Notable Accomplishments\n|-\n| [[Neil Best]] || Rugby player<ref>http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/sport/international-honours/neil-best/</ref>\n|-\n| [[Chris Brunt]] || Footballer<ref>http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/sport/international-honours/chris-brunt/</ref>\n|-\n| [[Brian Philip Davis]] || Filmmaker{{cn|date=September 2014}}\n|-\n| [[Stephen Scullion]] || Athlete<ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/other-sports/operation-transformation-from-couch-drunk-to-tokyo-olympian-1.3771092</ref>\n|-\n| [[Errol Hastings]] || Chief artisan baker at [[Sainsbury's|J Sainsbury plc]]<ref>http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/extra-curricular/home-economics/bakery-club.php{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Iain Lewers]] || Field Hockey Player <ref name=\"well200912\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/news-events/news/former-pupil-stars-for-great-britain-at-the-2012-olympics/|title=Former pupil stars for Great Britain at the 2012 Olympics|publisher=www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org|accessdate=4 November 2014|date=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"well071212\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/galleries/olympian-iain-lewers-returns-to-wcb/|title=Olympian Iain Lewers returns to WCB|publisher=www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org|accessdate=9 June 2019|date=7 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"well2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/sport/international-honours/iain-lewers/|title=Iain Lewers|publisher=www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wellingtoncollegebelfast.org/ Official website]\n\n{{Education in Northern Ireland}}\n\n[[Category:Wellington College Belfast| ]]\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Kids' Lit Quiz winners]]\n[[Category:Education in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1990]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in Northern Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:8668:ff00:10c2:6a62:90f7:c4b7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wellington_College_Belfast"}
{"title_page": "Mary and Rhoda", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = Mary and Rhoda\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| genre          = {{hlist|Comedy|Drama}}\n| director       = [[Barnet Kellman]]\n| based_on       = {{based_on|[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show|Characters]]|[[James L. Brooks]]<br>[[Allan Burns]]}}\n| executive_producer = [[Mary Tyler Moore]]<br />[[Susan B. Landau]]\n| producer       = Cecilia Kate Roque\n| writer         = [[Katie Ford (screenwriter)|Katie Ford]]\n| starring       = [[Mary Tyler Moore]]<br />[[Valerie Harper]]<br />[[Elon Gold]]<br />[[Christine Ebersole]]<br />[[Bethany Joy Lenz|Joie Lenz]]<br />[[Marisa Ryan]]\n| opentheme      = \"[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show opening sequence#Theme song|Love Is All Around]]\" by [[Joan Jett|Joan Jett & the Blackhearts]]\n| music          = [[David Kitay]]\n| cinematography = [[Adam Holender]]\n| editor         = Jeff Wishengrad\n| company        = [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]]<br />[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| network        = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| first_aired    = February 7, 2000\n| runtime        = 86 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| related        = ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]''<br />''[[Rhoda]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Mary and Rhoda''''' is a 2000 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[comedy-drama|comedy-drama film]] starring [[Mary Tyler Moore]] and [[Valerie Harper]] reprising their roles as [[Mary Richards]] and [[Rhoda Morgenstern]] from the 1970\u20131977 [[sitcom]] ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]''.\n\nAlthough the film is a [[List of television spin-offs|spin-off]] of ''The Mary Tyler Moore Show'', [[James L. Brooks]] and [[Allan Burns]] were not credited for creating the characters; neither they nor any other writers or producers from the original series was involved with this reunion film. It was the only film of any kind to be based on ''The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and the first production to be set in the series' \"universe\" in 18 years since the series finale of ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]'' in 1982.\n\n''Mary and Rhoda'' was written by [[Katie Ford (screenwriter)|Katie Ford]], executive produced by Mary Tyler Moore and [[Susan B. Landau]],<ref name=dline>{{cite news |first=Greg |last=Evans |title=Susan B. Landau Dies: \u2018Cool Runnings\u2019 Producer Was 65 |url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/susan-landau-dies-cool-runnings-producer-obituary-1202109258/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher= |date=2017-06-07 |accessdate=2017-06-25}}</ref> and directed by [[Barnet Kellman]]. During the opening title sequence, the original 1970 version of the theme song \"[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show opening sequence#Theme song|Love Is All Around]]\" is played and then switches to the 1996 version recorded by [[Joan Jett|Joan Jett & the Blackhearts]].\n\n==Plot==\nMary Richards-Cronin returns to [[New York City]] after spending four months in [[Europe]] (\u201cItaly, mostly,\u201d she tells a cabdriver) following the death of her [[Member of Congress|Congressman]] husband, Steven Cronin, in a rock-climbing accident. Rhoda Morgenstern-Rousseau also returns to her native New York to make a fresh start as a [[photographer]] after having lived in [[Paris]] for several years, where she has recently divorced her second husband, Jean-Pierre Rousseau.\n\nAfter decades of separation, Mary and Rhoda start to look for each other and eventually reunite outside Mary's apartment building in the Upper West Side of Manhattan (\u201c84th and Central Park West,\u201d Mary tells a cabdriver in an opening scene, though 415 Central Park West, at West 101st Street, was used for the building's exterior shots). The old friends visit Manhattan together and share the events of their lives over the intervening years; Mary then invites Rhoda, just returned to New York, to stay with her in her duplex apartment.\n\nMary reveals that following her departure from WJM-TV in Minneapolis as a news producer, she earned a master's degree in journalism and worked as a studio producer for [[ABC News]] in New York, until her daughter, Rose, was 12 and she decided to quit her job (eight years previously) to spend more time at home. Both Mary's and Rhoda's daughters are now in college \u2014 Mary's Rose is an English major at [[New York University|NYU]] and Rhoda's Meredith is a [[Pre-medical|pre-med]] student and living in residence at [[Barnard College]] \u2014 and are trying to build lives of their own, independent of their mothers.\n\nMary and Rhoda must also each revive their careers, as Rhoda is newly divorced and Mary has learned that her late husband of 20 years spent much of their money on his congressional campaign(s). Both women dread their prospects, as Mary is now 60 and Rhoda is around 58 and lacks confidence in her work as a photographer.\n\nMary finds a job as a segment producer for WNYT in New York, where she works under the station founder, Jonah Seimeier, who is little more than half Mary's age, and comes into conflict with the ethics of a vain anchor/field reporter, Cecile Andrews; Rhoda finds work as a fashion photographer's assistant, where, in addition to \u201cschlepping\", she mothers the young models and begins to take on more responsibility in the studio, as well as to exhibit her own photography independently; Rose suddenly quits school to try her hand at stand-up comedy, with a poor initial reception; and Meredith breaks off from her boyfriend.\n\nUltimately, all four women learn to conquer challenges in work and relationships, to forge their own identities and stand up for themselves.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mary Tyler Moore]] as [[Mary Richards|Mary Richards-Cronin]]\n* [[Valerie Harper]] as [[Rhoda Morgenstern|Rhoda Morgenstern-Rousseau]]\n* [[Elon Gold]] as Jonah Seimeier \n* [[Christine Ebersole]] as Cecile Andrews \n* [[Bethany Joy Lenz]] as Rose Cronin \n* [[Marisa Ryan]] as Meredith Rousseau\n\n==Viewer reaction and reception==\nThe film's producers reportedly wanted to make the characters \u201ccurrent\", and as a result, little time was spent in the characters discussing their former life in Minneapolis. This disappointed a number of longtime fans, as did the fact that former ''Mary Tyler Moore Show'' characters [[Lou Grant (fictional character)|Lou Grant]], [[Ted Baxter]], [[Murray Slaughter]], [[Phyllis Lindstrom]], [[List of minor characters on The Mary Tyler Moore Show|Georgette Baxter]] and [[Sue Ann Nivens]] were never directly referred to, nor were Rhoda's sister, Brenda Morgenstern, or her father, [[List of minor characters on The Mary Tyler Moore Show|Martin Morgenstern]]. (Indeed, Rhoda is shown staying at the \u201cChester Hotel\u201d when she first returns to New York, although she presumably still has family and friends in the city other than her daughter.) The only characters from ''The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and ''Rhoda'' to be mentioned was [[List of minor characters on The Mary Tyler Moore Show|Ida Morgenstern]], Rhoda's mother, and Dottie Richards, Mary's mother, though not by their names.\n\nCritical reaction was largely negative.  Phil Gallo of Variety wrote \"Taking characters from a great sitcom and moving them into this feel-good drama is a tough task, one that the script isn\u2019t up to...Fans of the great sitcom will certainly ask, \u201cWhere\u2019s the humor?\u201d\".<ref>https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/mary-and-rhoda-1117778646/</ref>  Terry Keleher of People singled out Rhoda's subplot as \"nearly laughless\", and summed up ''Mary and Rhoda'' with the comment \"Bottom Line: Can\u2019t measure up to the memories.\".<ref>https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-mary-and-rhoda-vol-53-no-5/</ref> Howard Rosenberg of The Los Angeles Times opined that ''Mary and Rhoda'' felt like \"a hologram with no center...\nthe tone here is much less witty than wistful, and re-bottling magic is difficult, perhaps even impossible, especially 25 or so years afterward.\"  Rosenberg was especially critical of the movie's \"preachy, smugly self-righteous ending.\".<ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-feb-07-ca-61798-story.html</ref> James Enderst of The Hartford Courant was particularly scathing, writing: \"The script is so stale, the plot so uninspired and the two hours so bereft of comedy ... If you loved ''The Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' stay away from ''Mary and Rhoda.''  It'll only depress you.\"\n\nEven reviews that expressed some regard for the project tended to heavily qualify their praise.  In a lukewarm review, Barbara Vancheri of The Pittsburgh Post Gazette wrote: \"As far as reunion movies go, it's not embarrassing - Mary Tyler Moore and Valerie Harper look fabulous - but it's also not up to the heady standards set by the 1970s series.\".<ref>http://old.post-gazette.com/tv/20000206owen.asp</ref> David Bainculli of the New York Daily News felt that \"At its best, though, it's no better than good ... dramatic moments strain too obviously for sentimentality, and comic ones sometimes work too hard to be noticed, like an overly loud relative at a dinner party.\"<ref>https://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/mary-bittersweet-reunion-rhoda-pal-article-1.861991</ref>\n\nAnticipating strong viewer interest, [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] scheduled the movie to air during February [[Nielsen ratings#Sweeps|sweeps]] and considered it a [[Television pilot|pilot]] for a weekly series. The program attracted 17.8 million viewers, beating out its main competition, [[CBS]]'s ''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]'', but critical reaction was so adverse ABC decided to abandon the project.\n\n==Early development==\nMary Tyler Moore and Valerie Harper announced in November 1997 that they had signed with [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] to reprise their roles as Mary and Rhoda in a new sitcom slated for the fall of 1998. ABC had ordered 13 episodes for the new show which featured Mary Richards and Rhoda Morgenstern as widows reunited by chance in New York after many years of estrangement, who each have a 20-something daughter named after the other (Mary's daughter is Rose Cronin and Rhoda's daughter is Meredith Rousseau).\n\nAccording to reports, ABC executives were not pleased with the script for the pilot episode and the proposed sitcom was scrapped altogether. By 1999, it was confirmed that Moore and Harper would reunite instead in the two-hour made-for-TV movie ''Mary and Rhoda'' which began filming on October 18, 1999.\n\n==Home media==\n''Mary and Rhoda'' was released on [[DVD]] in [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]] on April 20, 2004 by Studio Works Entertainment.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0137937}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|470108}}\n* {{Amg title|187046}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/187046/Mary-and-Rhoda/overview ''Mary and Rhoda''] at [[New York Times]]\n\n{{The Mary Tyler Moore Show}}\n{{Rhoda}}\n\n{{Barnet Kellman}}\n\n[[Category:2000 television films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films based on television series]]\n[[Category:Television series reunion films]]\n[[Category:The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]\n[[Category:ABC Movie of the Week]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = Mary and Rhoda\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Barnet Kellman]]\n| based_on       = {{based_on|[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show|Characters]]|[[James L. Brooks]]<br>[[Allan Burns]]}}\n| executive_producer = [[Mary Tyler Moore]]<br />[[Susan B. Landau]]\n| producer       = Cecilia Kate Roque\n| writer         = [[Katie Ford (screenwriter)|Katie Ford]]\n| starr